<a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=253870">Oaker Treeweaver</a></p>
</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/ufrodlin7th.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Frodlin7th</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>knows that Warriors are superior</span><br>  Posts: 8<br> <font color=#FF0000>(7/8/02 9:09:42 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthetavern.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=907.topic&index=91>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.steelwarrior.org/forum/p_die.gif" align=absmiddle>  More</span><hr size=1> So I was having a look at Hybrid Class skills/AA's etc, and am actually more disappointed than before.<br>
<br>
2h Bash:  One of the benefits of being a warrior in terms of melee was the ability to kick.   Now, this isn't much in terms of melee damage output, but it adds up a little.   Warriors have historically been able to use bash, but who the hell is a warrior with a shield?  At level 55, a warrior's kick also turns into a &quot;stun&quot; which will interrupt casting.   For those of us non-large race warriors, this is a MAJOR upgrade, as pre-55 medium and small race warriors who don't have a shield (about 100%) have no chance to interrput spells.  Our choices are <br>
<br>
A. Wield a shield making us FAR less effective<br>
<br>
B. Don't interrupt casters, and simply use kick for damage.<br>
<br>
Now, Paladins and SK's generally will through the levels switch between 1h and shield or 2h, making the choice that they had to make, either Wield 1h and shield, or 2h with no bash.   This is no longer the case.  They now get the same &quot;extra attack&quot; as we do which is a stun/interrupt while wielding a 2h weapon.  Again, there is no sense of &quot;balance&quot; here, there's no &quot;give or take&quot; for Knights, yet there is for Warriors.<br>
<br>
Physical Enhancement:<br>
<br>
This REALLY irritates me, here's the description:<br>
<br>
&quot;This ability adds an additional 2% to the Natural Durability, Combat Agility and Combat Stability archetypes.&quot;<br>
<br>
Paraphrased:<br>
<br>
&quot;This ability makes you a better tank than before&quot;<br>
<br>
Warriors DO NOT GET THIS.  Why the hell do warriors not get this?  This is asinine, so with AA skills, Knights get a skill which makes them better tanks while warriors don't?<br>
<br>
Body and Mind Rejuvenation:<br>
<br>
&quot;This skill adds an additional level to both of these abilities increasing even further the mana and health regeneration of the Paladin/Shadowknight. &quot;<br>
<br>
So, a Paladin or Shadowknight can get Extra Regen AND Mana Regen beyond regen 3 and clarity 3, can have Durability/Agility/Stability increased while warriors get neither.  Never mind that if regen is too slow, they can heal themselves quite quickly and easily.<br>
<br>
Slay Undead:<br>
<br>
Yap all you want about how it only increases your melee vs. undead by about 20%.   It's a passive skill, it's ALWAYS on, you ALWAYS have it, there's no refresh time, nothing.  <br>
<br>
Fearless:<br>
<br>
&quot;This ability makes the Paladin immune to all types of fear forever. This includes Dragon Fear.&quot;<br>
<br>
Warriors get 15 seconds of group fear immunity at level 3.   What does this mean?   While warriors are feared, Pallies and SK's are doing the tanking, and why the hell give it up then?  I mean, hell, the time it'd take for the warriors to get aggro back they'll just be feared again.<br>
<br>
We'll have to see what PoP has in store for us with regards to Fearing before further comment.<br>
<br>
Super Harmtouch/Leech Touch<br>
<br>
Uhh, to damage a foe for massive amounts of damage and be healed for the same amount....mana free once ever 90 mins.   <br>
<br>
This isn't touching into SCF3 Giving crit taps that heal for the same as the crit lands for.<br>
<br>
Fact is, with AA skills, WTF is a warrior for any more?   Those skills alone are a HUGE upgrade from pre-AA levels, whereas warriors have NOTHING but AE taunt, which is rarely used to AE taunt, and nothign a little snarepoop can't replace.<br>
<br>
See the above comments re: monks and better mitigation/HP/AC and FAR more offensively powerful.<br>
<br>
Warriors are now broken<br>
<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2F2F4F><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/ukraydak.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Kraydak</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>knows that Warriors are superior</span><br>  Posts: 2<br> <font color=#FF0000>(7/8/02 10:18:20 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthetavern.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=907.topic&index=92>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.steelwarrior.org/forum/p_die.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: More</span><hr size=1> Having thought a bit more, I might have come up with a set of changes that would help a lot and be fairly easily codeable (at least, probably).<br>
<br>
1) Face it, people have too many hp in general.  So mess with hp buff stacking some (move Shaman buffs to the symbol slot, move the shielding line to its *own* slot and drastically increase its value, put all other hp buffs such as BMB in one slot).  Then put a multiplier on the total buff+gear hp according to class, along the lines of warrior=1, knight=.8, most everyone else .6 and int caster .4<br>
<br>
This would be a *drastic* nerf, but one that is probably needed to repair the class based hp differences that were initially intended (and to reduce the sky high hp totals a little).<br>
<br>
2)  Fix the mitigation AC softcap.  Putting a line the that does somthing like CS=CS+(AC-Attack)/25 or so should work (ie, you gain an effective 1 point of CS for every 25 points of AC past a certain threshhold dependant on the mob's attack rating).<br>
<br>
3) The above does not affect MTing, so, in the same manner that monks have a better attack table, let warriors decrease a mobs damage bonus (not damage interval) by 1%/lvl.  This has the advantage of being a guaranteed reduction in damage and hence modifies MTing.  Make sure warriors get the best AC gear, followed by knights, rangers/rogues etc...<br>
<br>
4) Drop the duration of Evasive/Defensive to 30 seconds, drop the attack penalty and slightly increase their effects.  They become good disciplines for starting hard fights (buy time to debuff/start a CH rotation) but they lose their actual damage reduction effects.  Defensive would stop being a one-shot wonder.<br>
<br>
5) The melee balancing worked fine for Velious, but the Luclin high AC mobs had the hopefully unforseen effect of drastically increasing the value of 2handers, and that combined with the introduction of innumberable knight 2handers ruined the balance.  I'd suggest allowing warriors to do a minimum damage on a hit (pre-damage bonus) of 10% of weapons damage/lvl above 60.  So a lvl 60 with a 15/20 weapon in off hand would do a minimum of 15 damage on a hit.  This would have little effect off Luclin and would fix Luclin's stupidity.  Other dual-wielding classes might as well take advantage of this, leaving knights as the defensive hybrids behind.<br>
<br>
6) If the above isn't sufficient, allow dual-wielders to dual-parry (get a second parry chance based on dual-wield skill if the first fails).  Tweak it so a dual wielder has a similar chance to parry as a monk has to block.<br>
<br>
-Kraydak<br>
<br>
